<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
The name, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bashir &amp; Ma" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Carinostigmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carinostigmus capiconvergens" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capiconvergens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Carinostigmus capiconvergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is derived from the Latin words 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">caput</emphasis>
(= head) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">con-vergo</emphasis>
(= converge), referring to the head from above with temples distinctly convergent posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
